'''Jenaro Flores Santos''' (b. September 19, 1941, [[Antipampa]]<ref>Rocha Monroy, Ram<U+00F3>n, Eduardo Acevedo, and Lorenzo Soliz Tito. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=k1ixVfUkStEC Jenaro Flores Santos: l<U+00ED>der fundador de la CSUTCB y de la resistencia a las dictaduras militares]''. L<U+00ED>deres contempor<U+00E1>neos del movimiento campesino ind<U+00ED>gena de Bolivia, no. 1. La Paz, Bolivia: CIPCA, 2006. p. 8</ref>), a Bolivian [[trade union]] leader and politician. Flores Santos was the founder of the [[CSUTCB]]. He also played a prominent role in formulating ''katarismo'' as a distinct trend in the social and political struggles in Bolivia.<ref>Rocha Monroy, Ram<U+00F3>n, Eduardo Acevedo, and Lorenzo Soliz Tito. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=k1ixVfUkStEC Jenaro Flores Santos: l<U+00ED>der fundador de la CSUTCB y de la resistencia a las dictaduras militares]''. L<U+00ED>deres contempor<U+00E1>neos del movimiento campesino ind<U+00ED>gena de Bolivia, no. 1. La Paz, Bolivia: CIPCA, 2006. p. 6</ref>

Flores Santos did his military service at the Waldo Ballivi<U+00E1>n Regiment in 1965. During his military service he witnessed to the suppression of the popular militias (created after the 1952 revolution), an event that impacted his political orientation. Later he begun studies at the Faculty of Law at the [[Universidad Mayor de San Andr<U+00E9>s]]. There he founded, along with other students from his home province, the Juli<U+00E1>n Apaza University Movement (MUJA).<ref>Rocha Monroy, Ram<U+00F3>n, Eduardo Acevedo, and Lorenzo Soliz Tito. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=k1ixVfUkStEC Jenaro Flores Santos: l<U+00ED>der fundador de la CSUTCB y de la resistencia a las dictaduras militares]''. L<U+00ED>deres contempor<U+00E1>neos del movimiento campesino ind<U+00ED>gena de Bolivia, no. 1. La Paz, Bolivia: CIPCA, 2006. p. 9</ref> From 1968, Flores Santos emerged as the leader of the La Paz-based Aymara nucleus of peasant activists that sought to challenge the Military-Peasant Pact.<ref>Yashar, Deborah J. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=gvE5Mufp6R8C Contesting Citizenship in Latin America: The Rise of Indigenous Movements and the Postliberal Challenge]''. Cambridge studies in contentious politics. Cambridge ;New York: Cambridge Univ. Press, 2005. p. 171</ref>

In January 1969, Flores Santos became the local head of the trade union in Antipampa, and two months later he became the union head for the [[Aroma province]]. In June 1969 he became the executive secretary of the La Paz Department Farmer-Labourers Federation (FDTCLP).<ref name="back">Rocha Monroy, Ram<U+00F3>n, Eduardo Acevedo, and Lorenzo Soliz Tito. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=k1ixVfUkStEC Jenaro Flores Santos: l<U+00ED>der fundador de la CSUTCB y de la resistencia a las dictaduras militares]''. L<U+00ED>deres contempor<U+00E1>neos del movimiento campesino ind<U+00ED>gena de Bolivia, no. 1. La Paz, Bolivia: CIPCA, 2006. p. Back Cover</ref> In connection with his arrival to the FDTCLP leadership, the name "[[Tupaj Katari]]" was added the the name of the organization.<ref>Garc<U+00ED>a Jord<U+00E1>n, Pilar, and Miquel Izard. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=Hy2vS-WGWLAC Conquista y resistencia en la historia de Am<U+00E9>rica: [encuentro-debate, Barcelona, 1991] = Conquesta i resist<U+00E8>ncia en la hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E9>rica]''. Am<U+00E9>rica Latina, Ayer y Hoy : ... encuentro debate = Am<U+00E8>rica Llatina, Ahir i Avui / [Departament d'Antropologia Social, Hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E8>rica i Africa de la Universitat de Barcelona], 3. Barcelona: Univ, 1992. p. 411</ref>

In 1970 Flores Santos took part in agrarian struggles in the [[La Paz Department, Bolivia|La Paz Department]], with seizures of land areas. These moves were later legalized through an agrarian reform the same year.<ref name="back"/> In August 1971, at its sixth congress (organized by the government), Flores Santos was elected executive secretary of the National Farmer-Labourer Confederation of Bolivia (''Confederaci<U+00F3>n Nacional de Trabajadores Campesinos de Bolivia'', CNTCB).<ref>Garc<U+00ED>a Jord<U+00E1>n, Pilar, and Miquel Izard. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=Hy2vS-WGWLAC Conquista y resistencia en la historia de Am<U+00E9>rica: [encuentro-debate, Barcelona, 1991] = Conquesta i resist<U+00E8>ncia en la hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E9>rica]''. Am<U+00E9>rica Latina, Ayer y Hoy : ... encuentro debate = Am<U+00E8>rica Llatina, Ahir i Avui / [Departament d'Antropologia Social, Hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E8>rica i Africa de la Universitat de Barcelona], 3. Barcelona: Univ, 1992. p. 412</ref>

In 1971 Flores Santos was forced into exile to [[Chile]]. He returned the next year, to organize underground resistance against the military government.<ref name="back"/>

In 1978 he was one of the founders of the Tupaj Katari Revolutionary Movement (MRTK).<ref name="p414">Garc<U+00ED>a Jord<U+00E1>n, Pilar, and Miquel Izard. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=Hy2vS-WGWLAC Conquista y resistencia en la historia de Am<U+00E9>rica: [encuentro-debate, Barcelona, 1991] = Conquesta i resist<U+00E8>ncia en la hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E9>rica]''. Am<U+00E9>rica Latina, Ayer y Hoy : ... encuentro debate = Am<U+00E8>rica Llatina, Ahir i Avui / [Departament d'Antropologia Social, Hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E8>rica i Africa de la Universitat de Barcelona], 3. Barcelona: Univ, 1992. p. 414</ref>

On June 26, 1979 the CSTUCB was founded with Flores Santos as its founding executive secretary. In November 1979 he led struggles against a new military coup, organizing blockades of highways across the country. During the military government of Garc<U+00ED>a Meza, he served as the clandestine executive secretary of the [[Central Obrera Boliviana]] (COB).<ref name="back"/> The coup of Garc<U+00ED>a Meza had caught the COB leadership by surpsrise, and only Flores Santos who had left a COB leadership meeting to make a phone-call had escaped arrest.<ref>Stern, Steve J. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=vRd3T0IY_nMC Resistance, Rebellion, and Consciousness in the Andean Peasant World, 18th to 20th Centuries]''. Madison, Wis: University of Wisconsin Press, 1987. </ref> This was the first time a peasant leader was in charge of COB.<ref name="p414"/> His tenure as COB leader ended after being shot by a military patrol on June 18, 1981, after which he was paralyzed.<ref name="back"/><ref>Gianotten, Vera. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=YhEAhSEJV1kC CIPCA y poder campesino ind<U+00ED>gena: 35 a<U+00F1>os de historia]''. La Paz, Bolivia: CIPCA, 2006. p. 384</ref>

In the 1980s, the ''katarista'' movement was divided into two political parties. Flores Santos became the leader of one of them, FULKA.<ref>Garc<U+00ED>a Jord<U+00E1>n, Pilar, and Miquel Izard. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=Hy2vS-WGWLAC Conquista y resistencia en la historia de Am<U+00E9>rica: [encuentro-debate, Barcelona, 1991] = Conquesta i resist<U+00E8>ncia en la hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E9>rica]''. Am<U+00E9>rica Latina, Ayer y Hoy : ... encuentro debate = Am<U+00E8>rica Llatina, Ahir i Avui / [Departament d'Antropologia Social, Hist<U+00F2>ria d'Am<U+00E8>rica i Africa de la Universitat de Barcelona], 3. Barcelona: Univ, 1992. p. 415</ref>

